The Australian National University College of Engineering and Computer Science (CECS) internship program, formally known as the ANU Internship Program (ANIP), provides a structured pathway for students to gain industry experience while earning academic credit. In 2026, over **340 CECS students** participated in ANIP placements, reflecting a **22% increase** from the previous year. The program maintains an **87% host satisfaction rate**, with more than **150 active industry partners** across Australia. Understanding the placement process is critical for students aiming to integrate practical work experience with their degree requirements.

## ANIP Program Overview and Structure

The ANU Internship Program operates as a **curricular internship model**, meaning placements are embedded within academic programs rather than offered as extracurricular opportunities. CECS students can undertake internships through course codes **ENGN3100, ENGN3200, COMP3100, or COMP3200**, depending on their discipline and placement duration.

The program supports **two placement formats**: a standard 20-day internship (approximately **140 hours**) for 6 credit points, and an extended 30-day internship (approximately **210 hours**) for 12 credit points. International students must ensure placements comply with **visa work limitations**, typically capped at 48 hours per fortnight during teaching periods.

**Placement cycles operate year-round**, with major intake periods aligned to Semester 1 (February to June) and Semester 2 (July to November). Students may also undertake placements during summer and winter breaks, provided host organisations agree to the timing. The CECS Internship Office coordinates all administrative aspects, including insurance coverage, legal agreements, and academic supervision.

## ANIP Eligibility Requirements and GPA Thresholds

Eligibility for ANIP involves meeting both **academic progression requirements** and **course-specific prerequisites**. Students must have completed a minimum of **72 credit points** toward their degree before commencing an internship. This ensures participants possess adequate foundational knowledge before entering professional environments.

The **GPA requirement for ANIP eligibility** is set at a minimum of **4.0 on the ANU 7-point scale**. This threshold applies across all CECS disciplines, including software engineering, computer science, mechatronics, and environmental engineering. Students with GPAs between **4.0 and 4.5** receive additional support through pre-placement workshops covering workplace communication and professional expectations.

**International students** must demonstrate English language proficiency equivalent to an IELTS score of **6.5 overall with no band below 6.0**, or hold a recognised qualification from an English-medium institution. Additionally, students must maintain **full-time enrolment status** throughout the placement period, with the internship course counting toward their study load.

Students on **academic probation or with outstanding disciplinary matters** are ineligible until these issues are resolved. The CECS Internship Office conducts eligibility checks at the point of application and again before placement commencement.

## Host Matching Process and Industry Partner Engagement

The host matching process follows a **structured yet flexible framework** designed to align student capabilities with organisational needs. Students begin by submitting an **expression of interest** through the ANIP online portal, which includes their academic transcript, a tailored resume, and a statement addressing their placement preferences.

**Host matching operates on a dual-stream model**. In the **direct-matching stream**, the CECS Internship Office reviews student profiles and forwards shortlisted candidates to host organisations. Hosts then conduct interviews and make final selection decisions. This stream accounts for approximately **65% of placements** in 2026.

The **self-sourced stream** allows students to identify and approach potential host organisations independently. Students must submit a **Host Organisation Approval Form** detailing the proposed project, supervisor qualifications, and workplace safety arrangements. The CECS team assesses these proposals within **10 business days**. In 2026, self-sourced placements represented **28% of total internships**, with the remaining **7%** coming through university research partnerships.

**Host organisations range from multinational corporations** like Accenture, Deloitte, and Microsoft Australia, to Canberra-based startups, government agencies such as the **Australian Signals Directorate**, and research institutions including **CSIRO**. The program maintains a **minimum standard for host supervisors**, requiring them to hold a relevant degree or equivalent professional experience of at least **three years**.

## Credit Arrangements and Academic Assessment

Credit arrangements for CECS internships are governed by the **ANU Coursework Awards Policy** and specific program rules. Students undertaking a **6-credit-point placement** must complete the standard 140-hour internship alongside assessment tasks that typically include a **reflective journal, a project report (3,000 to 4,000 words), and a host supervisor evaluation**.

The **12-credit-point extended placement** requires a more substantial academic output, often including a **technical project deliverable** agreed upon by the student, host supervisor, and academic convenor. This might involve a software prototype, engineering design document, or research paper. Assessment weightings for the extended placement are generally split as **40% host evaluation, 30% project deliverable, and 30% reflective report**.

**Credit points earned through ANIP** count toward elective requirements in most CECS degrees. For Bachelor of Engineering (Honours) students, the 12-credit-point internship can substitute for one **engineering elective** or, in some cases, contribute to the **required 60 days of industrial experience** mandated by Engineers Australia accreditation standards.

**Grading follows the standard ANU scale**, from High Distinction to Fail. The host supervisor evaluation contributes to the final grade but does not solely determine it. Academic convenors moderate all assessments to ensure consistency across placement types and host organisations.

## Application Timeline and Key Dates for 2026

The ANIP application timeline for 2026 includes **four major rounds** to accommodate different placement periods. Students planning a **Semester 1 placement** should apply by **15 November 2025**, with host matching occurring through December and January. **Semester 2 placement applications** close on **15 May 2026**, with matching completed by late June.

**Summer placement applications** for the December 2026 to February 2027 period open on **1 August 2026** and close on **15 September 2026**. Winter intensive placements follow a shorter timeline, with applications due by **15 April 2026** for placements during the July break.

Late applications may be considered on a **case-by-case basis** if host organisations have unfilled positions. However, students submitting after the deadline face **reduced placement options** and cannot be guaranteed a match. The CECS Internship Office recommends submitting applications **at least six weeks before** the intended placement start date.

**Offer letters are typically issued** within three weeks of the host interview. Students must accept or decline offers within **five business days**. Declining an offer without documented extenuating circumstances may affect eligibility for future rounds.

## Preparing a Competitive ANIP Application

A strong ANIP application requires attention to both **academic documentation and professional presentation**. Students should update their ANU academic transcript to include the most recent semester results before applying. The transcript must show a **cumulative GPA of 4.0 or above**, with individual course grades visible.

**Resume preparation** should follow Australian industry standards, typically a **two-page document** highlighting relevant coursework, technical skills, previous work experience, and extracurricular involvement. The CECS Careers Service offers **free resume reviews** and mock interviews for ANIP applicants. In 2026, students who utilised these services had a **34% higher placement success rate** than those who did not.

The **statement of interest** is a critical component that many students underestimate. Effective statements address **specific host organisations or industry sectors**, explain how the placement connects to career goals, and demonstrate knowledge of the host's work. Generic statements rarely succeed in competitive matching rounds.

**Technical portfolios** are strongly recommended for computing students applying to software development or data science roles. A GitHub profile with **at least three substantive projects**, contributions to open-source software, or evidence of hackathon participation can differentiate candidates. Engineering students benefit from including **design project documentation** or laboratory reports that showcase analytical abilities.

## Workplace Integration and Professional Conduct

Once placed, students must complete the **ANU Workplace Induction Module** before commencing on-site work. This online module covers workplace health and safety, professional ethics, confidentiality obligations, and the ANU Code of Conduct. Completion is verified by the CECS Internship Office before the placement start date.

**Students are expected to adhere to host organisation policies**, including working hours, dress codes, and IT usage guidelines. The standard ANIP placement requires attendance during regular business hours, though flexible arrangements may be negotiated with host supervisors. Any absences must be reported to both the host supervisor and the academic convenor within **24 hours**.

**Regular check-ins** form part of the program structure. The academic convenor contacts students at the **two-week and midpoint marks** of the placement to monitor progress and address any concerns. Host supervisors complete a **mid-placement review** that identifies areas for improvement before the final evaluation.

**Insurance coverage** is provided through ANU's corporate policies, including public liability, professional indemnity, and personal accident insurance. Students on unpaid placements may be eligible for **travel concessions** or, in some cases, a **living allowance bursary** of up to **$3,000 AUD**, subject to approval based on financial need and placement location.

## FAQ

**What is the minimum GPA for ANIP eligibility in 2026?**

The minimum GPA requirement is **4.0 on the ANU 7-point scale**. This applies to all CECS students regardless of discipline. Students with GPAs slightly below this threshold may request a special consideration review if they have extenuating circumstances, such as documented medical conditions or significant personal hardship during previous semesters.

**How many credit points can I earn through an ANU internship?**

Students can earn either **6 credit points** for a 20-day placement (approximately 140 hours) or **12 credit points** for a 30-day extended placement (approximately 210 hours). Bachelor of Engineering (Honours) students may use the 12-credit-point internship to partially satisfy the **60-day industrial experience requirement** mandated by Engineers Australia.

**Can international students participate in ANIP placements?**

Yes, international students are eligible for ANIP provided they meet the standard academic requirements and hold a valid student visa with work rights. Placements must comply with the **48-hour-per-fortnight work limitation** during teaching periods. During scheduled university breaks, this limitation does not apply, allowing full-time placement engagement.

**What happens if I cannot find a host through the matching process?**

Students who do not secure a placement through the direct-matching stream may explore the **self-sourced stream** by identifying their own host organisation. The CECS Internship Office provides guidance on approaching potential hosts and reviews all self-sourced proposals. If placement remains unsuccessful, students may defer their application to the next available round or consider alternative elective courses.

**Are ANIP placements paid or unpaid?**

ANIP placements may be **paid or unpaid**, depending on the host organisation. Approximately **45% of 2026 placements** included some form of remuneration, ranging from stipends of **$500 to $1,200 AUD per week** to hourly rates aligned with industry awards. Unpaid placements remain common in research institutions and government agencies, where the primary value lies in professional experience and academic credit.

